---
import SiteLayout from '../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';

export const meta = {
  title: "Electric vs Manual Toothbrush Comparison",
  description: "Side-by-side comparison of electric and manual toothbrushes. See plaque removal data, cost analysis, and dentist recommendations to choose the right brush.",
  category: 'list'
};

const faqList = [
  { q: "How much more plaque does an electric toothbrush remove?", a: "Studies show that electric toothbrushes remove 21% more plaque on average compared to manual brushing over a three-month period." },
  { q: "How often should I replace my toothbrush head?", a: "You should replace your manual toothbrush or electric toothbrush head every 3 to 4 months, or sooner if the bristles become frayed." },
  { q: "What is the recommended brushing duration and pressure?", a: "Dentists recommend brushing for a full two minutes, twice a day. Apply gentle pressure; pressing too hard can damage your enamel and irritate your gums." },
  { q: "How often should I get a dental check-up?", a: "Most people should visit the dentist for a check-up and professional cleaning every six months to maintain optimal oral health." },
  { q: "What are the signs that I need to see a dentist immediately?", a: "Warning signs include severe toothaches, bleeding or swollen gums, chronic bad breath, extreme tooth sensitivity, and loose teeth." }
];

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "name": "Best Electric Toothbrush vs Manual 2026",
    "url": "https://bodycount.photonbuilder.com/electric-vs-manual-toothbrush",
    "description": "Comprehensive oral health guide comparing electric vs manual toothbrushes. Learn about brushing techniques, flossing, mouthwash, and dental check-ups."
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": faqList.map(faq => ({
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": faq.q,
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": faq.a
      }
    }))
  }
];

const brandsList = [
  { item: 'Sonicare DiamondClean', brand: 'Philips', tier: 'Premium', space: 'Countertop', type: 'Sonic', coreUse: 'Whitening/Plaque' },
  { item: 'Oral-B iO Series 9', brand: 'Oral-B', tier: 'Premium', space: 'Countertop', type: 'Oscillating', coreUse: 'Deep Clean/Tracking' },
  { item: 'Sonicare ProtectiveClean', brand: 'Philips', tier: 'Mid-Range', space: 'Compact', type: 'Sonic', coreUse: 'Daily Cleaning' },
  { item: 'Oral-B Pro 1000', brand: 'Oral-B', tier: 'Budget', space: 'Compact', type: 'Oscillating', coreUse: 'Plaque Removal' }
];

---

<SiteLayout
  site="bodycount"
  title={meta.title}
  description={meta.description}
  canonical="https://bodycount.photonbuilder.com/electric-vs-manual-toothbrush"
  schema={schema}
>
  <style>
    /* Table Styles */
    .table-container {
      background: var(--card-bg);
      border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
      border-radius: 12px;
      overflow-x: auto;
      margin-bottom: 4rem;
    }

    table {
      width: 100%;
      border-collapse: collapse;
      text-align: left;
    }

    th {
      background: var(--chart-header);
      padding: 1rem 1.5rem;
      font-weight: 600;
      color: var(--text-secondary);
      border-bottom: 2px solid var(--border-color);
      white-space: nowrap;
    }

    td {
      padding: 1rem 1.5rem;
      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color);
      color: var(--text-primary);
    }

    tr:last-child td {
      border-bottom: none;
    }
  </style>

  <div>
    <h1>Best Electric Toothbrush vs Manual</h1>
    <p>
      A comprehensive oral health guide on electric vs manual toothbrushes, brushing technique, flossing, mouthwash, and dentist check-ups.
    </p>

    <h2>Electric vs Manual: Pros & Cons</h2>
    <p>
      Choosing between an electric and manual toothbrush often comes down to personal preference, but science points towards one clear winner. Studies show that electric toothbrushes remove <strong>21% more plaque</strong> over a three-month period compared to manual brushing. They also help reduce gingivitis significantly.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Electric Pros:</strong> Built-in timers, pressure sensors to prevent over-brushing, easier for people with limited mobility, superior plaque removal.</li>
      <li><strong>Electric Cons:</strong> Higher upfront cost, requires charging, replacement heads can be expensive.</li>
      <li><strong>Manual Pros:</strong> Affordable, accessible everywhere, no batteries required, easy to travel with.</li>
      <li><strong>Manual Cons:</strong> Heavily reliant on proper user technique, no built-in timer, higher risk of brushing too hard.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Oral Care Guide</h2>

    <h3>Brushing Technique</h3>
    <p><strong>Manual:</strong> Use small, circular motions at a 45-degree angle to the gums.</p>
    <p><strong>Electric:</strong> Guide the brush slowly from tooth to tooth, letting it do the work without scrubbing.</p>

    <h3>Recommended Duration and Pressure</h3>
    <p>Dentists recommend brushing for a full two minutes, twice a day. Apply gentle pressure; pressing too hard can damage your enamel and irritate your gums.</p>

    <h3>Flossing Guide</h3>
    <p>Use about 18 inches of floss. Curve it into a C-shape around each tooth and gently slide it up and down under the gumline.</p>

    <h3>Mouthwash Types</h3>
    <p>Fluoride mouthwash prevents decay, while antiseptic reduces plaque and gingivitis. Use after brushing and flossing.</p>

    <h3>Replacement Schedule</h3>
    <p>Replace manual toothbrushes or electric brush heads every 3 to 4 months. Frayed bristles lose effectiveness and harbor bacteria.</p>

    <h3>Dental Check-ups</h3>
    <p>Most people should visit the dentist for a check-up and professional cleaning every six months to maintain optimal oral health.</p>

    <h3>Signs You Need a Dentist</h3>
    <p>Warning signs include severe toothaches, bleeding or swollen gums, chronic bad breath, extreme tooth sensitivity, and loose teeth.</p>

    <h2>Compare Best Electric Toothbrushes</h2>
    <div class="table-container">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Model</th>
            <th>Brand</th>
            <th>Price Tier</th>
            <th>Space Required</th>
            <th>Type</th>
            <th>Core Feature</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {brandsList.map(brand => (
            <tr>
              <td><strong>{brand.item}</strong></td>
              <td>{brand.brand}</td>
              <td>{brand.tier}</td>
              <td>{brand.space}</td>
              <td>{brand.type}</td>
              <td>{brand.coreUse}</td>
